<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="792" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d792">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/154</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Kirby Lumber Company</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Houston, Texas</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-05">
                                <hi rend="italic">August 5, 1914</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Telegraph companies refuse to handle code messages for Porto Rico
                            advising French cable New York to Porto Rico regulations demand plain
                            language and full address. Must these revisions be complied with on
                            messages from one part of United States to another? We, of course,
                            considering Porto Rico United States territory and business in a sense
                            interstate.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirby Lumber Company</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>